<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency says 
regulations to control the volatility of gasoline and the recovery 
of gasoline fumes could be twice as effective as originally 
expected 
as a result cities close to complying with federal clean air 
standards will get a greater than expected reduction in ozone when 
epa adopts the new rules 
implementation of the regulations had been expected to help 
antipollution efforts but epa administrator lee m thomas said 
thursday the benefit would be much greater than previously believed 
earlier epa calculations had indicated the gasoline regulations 
would reduce the emission of urban hydrocarbons to the atmosphere 
by 10 percent to 15 percent thomas said 
it could be as much as twice that thomas said 
some cities are so close to complying with the standard that 
they had been expected to come into compliance simply through the 
retirement of older morepolluting vehicles thomas said he did 
not know how many cities would benefit from the new findings 
but those helped the most will be areas where peak readings of 
ozone are in the 014 parts per million range and below he 
said some cities may find that measures such as pollution 
inspections of cars will be unnecessary 
there are 38 cities with peak readings of 014 ppm or below on 
epas list of the 68 urban and rural areas that have failed to meet 
the nations ozone standard 
gasoline fumes react in sunlight with nitrogen oxides from all 
fuel combustion to produce ozone which is harmful to the lungs 
ozone is the constituent of urban smog that makes the chest feel 
tight 
the federal standard calls for limiting peak ozone to 012 parts 
per million and limiting excursions above that to no more than one 
hour per year 
gasoline vapor emissions to the atmosphere will be reduced more 
than expected because the planned regulations will sharply reduce 
what analysts call running losses or the evaporation of 
gasoline from the tank and other fuel system components while the 
car is moving 
current cars must meet strict standards for emission of unburned 
gasoline vapor out the tailpipe and for evaporation 
evaporation is controlled by a vapor recovery system which 
stores gasoline vapor in a cannister of activated charcoal until 
they can be recycled to the tank it is tested by collecting vapor 
emitted when a car is stationary and for this the agency uses a 
test fuel whose volatility has remained unchanged since 1975 
actual volatility has increased sharply since then and on hot 
days it can overwhelm the cannister 
in such circumstances the car can emit to the atmosphere 25 
times more gasoline vapor than is permitted out the exhaust 
the volatility standard will reduce these emissions and the 
vapor recovery regulation will ensure that more of them are 
captured agency officials say the epa says this would remove a 
large source of urban ozone that the agency had not known was there 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

