<TEXT>
boston university rejected student protests and 
issued strict new rules prohibiting students from having overnight 
guests of the opposite sex and reducing the amount of alcohol in 
dormitories 
the rules were released thursday a day after 2000 students 
converged on campus for a threehour demonstration against the 
visitation policy 
all of life after 11 pm has been banned at bu jamie 
sanbonmatsu a senior at the college of liberal arts told the 
crowd the administration is stunting our growth and development 
by denying us the right to make decisions 
under the new guidelines some of which go into effect in late 
fall and others during spring guests must display identification 
cards and leave the dormitory by 11 pm on weekdays and 1 am on 
weekends 
overnight stays by members of the same sex will be allowed if 
roommates agree but members of the opposite sex will not be 
allowed overnight 
the amount of alcohol allowed into the dorms will be limited to 
a sixpack of beer and a liter of other alcoholic beverages for 
students over age 21 
kevin carleton a university spokesman said wednesdays protest 
did not faze bu officials 
i dont think any demonstration would have an effect said 
carleton what can have an effect is a reasonable discussion 
officials said they based their decision on concerns stated by 
students staff and parents that residences too often have failed 
to provide the kind of environment where an individual can quietly 
study and have his or her right to privacy respected 
bu officials cited problems such as parties latenight group 
study and peer pressure to put up with overnight guests there are 
8700 students housed in university residence halls 
parietal rules were dropped by many american colleges and 
universities including bu in the 1960s and 70s 
</TEXT>
