<TEXT>
former president gerald r ford says the legal 
restrictions of the controversial war powers act never caused him 
to change any of the decisions he made during his presidency 
i did what i felt had to be done the former president told 
a senate subcommittee 
fords comment came thursday in response to a question from sen 
larry pressler rsd about whether any of fords national 
security decisions were affected by the executive branch 
restrictions contained in the 1973 law 
ford is a strong opponent of the law as have been all 
presidents since the measure was enacted over president nixons 
veto the law was a congressional attempt to check some of the 
power which legislators felt had greatly deepened the american role 
in the vietnam war 
the law directs the white house to send congress a report within 
48 hours after us military personnel are sent to areas of 
imminent hostilities those forces must then be withdrawn within 60 
days or in some cases 90 days unless congress votes to allow them 
to remain 
ford told the foreign relations subcommittee set up to study the 
war powers act that he and his successors sent 19 reports to 
congress under the law although the documents werent submitted 
under provisions of the act that could trigger the 60day 
withdrawal period 
he added in the 15 years of the war powers resolution its 
never been implemented never its a dormant piece of 
legislation it ought to be repealed 
but ford added that im practical i dont think it will be 
repealed i support the kind of amendments proposed in a reform 
backed by leaders of both parties 
the changes would eliminate the 60 or 90day automatic 
withdrawal period and would replace the reporting requirement with 
a requirement that a president consult with house and senate 
leaders about major national security decisions 
the latest war powers fights have centered on president reagans 
policy of protecting reflagged kuwaiti tankers in the persian gulf 
reagan has refused to invoke the law there have been seven 
votes in congress on attempts to force the administration to comply 
with the law but all have failed 
abraham d sofaer the state department legal adviser also 
argued that the law is unconstitutional 
it incoporates a view of the relative powers of the political 
branches of our government and of their proper roles that is at 
odds with the constitutions scheme and with over 200 years of 
relatively consistent experience sofaer said 
sofaer also objected to the 60day restriction because the 
imposition of arbitrary and inflexible deadlines interferes with 
the effective and successful completion of the initiative 
undertaken by the president 
such limits may signal a divided nation giving our 
adversaries a basis for hoping that the president may be forced to 
desist or at least feel pressured to do so he explained 
</TEXT>
