<TEXT>
the incessant surf rolled in a little 
higher than normal and even though it was late summer the peak 
time for tropical storms people werent too concerned 
after all this was galveston the largest and most prosperous 
town in texas the wall steet of the southwest and it had 
weathered storms before 
in september 1900 in the days before radio and satellite 
photographs people had no idea that out in the gulf of mexico a 
monster storm was brewing that would change texas history and bring 
death and terror on a scale that never has been seen before or 
since in the united states 
on sept 8 1900 galveston was home to nearly 38000 people 
when the sun rose the next day nearly onesixth of the citys 
residents were dead victims of buildings toppled by winds and 
waves drowned in the 15foot storm surge mangled by flying debris 
or washed out to sea 
the death toll was put at 6000 but its uncertain how many 
thousands of others were lost 
nobody knows the complete story of what happened at galveston 
nobody ever will know john edward weems wrote in his classic 
account of the storm a weekend in september 
ironically the book written in 1956 was rereleased this 
month to mark the 88th anniversary of the great galveston storm 
most of them wanted to talk weems says now recalling his 
conversations with storm survivors the tragedies were still with 
them but enough time had passed so they could talk about them 
i got the idea some of them might be paying respect to their 
dead friends and relatives by talking about them 
although weems believes all the hundreds of survivors he 
interviewed have died since jennie graham karboski is among the 
few still living who were there and what she remembers most is the 
water angrily rising and the bodies floating everywhere 
mrs karboski is now 100 and lives with her daughter in houston 
she was 12 and growing up in galveston when the storm hit 
they tried to have mass burials at sea but the next morning 
many floated back in on the surf she told the houston chronicle 
this week the men had to dig trenches and burn them my dad said 
they kept the work crews drunk they had to 
after a harrowing journey by rowboat and horse cart mrs 
karboskis family found shelter in a catholic seminary 
others who survived huddled in a lighthouse or a stormtossed 
ship or crammed inside the upper stories of their homes others 
clung to wreckage until the waters receded 
perhaps the most lasting monument to the 1900 storm is the 
galveston seawall a concrete embankment 17 feet above mean low 
tide built after the great storm to ward off future huge storm 
surges it has helped to moderate damage from hurricanes since 
a more significant effect however was that many businessmen 
who considered galveston the hub of activity for texas decided they 
would not put themselves through another such storm 
they moved inland about 50 miles to a mosquitoinfested swamp 
town called houston which 88 years later is the nations 
fourthlargest city 
