<TEXT>
when president reagan switched the other day 
and decided to release overdue payments to the united nations it 
was another sign that as far as us foreign policy is concerned 
his views have undergone extensive alteration since he entered the 
white house nearly eight years ago 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater explained the surprising 
switch on the dues as based on a determination by reagan that the 
united nations had reformed its operation 
that doesnt alter the fact however that one of the tenets of 
the political philosophy that nurtured reagan and gave identity to 
his pursuit of the presidency was severe skepticism of the united 
nations 
conservatives always have complained that the united states paid 
a disproportionate share of the un bills while serving as a 
convenient target of the soviet bloc and the socalled nonaligned 
countries 
but reagan told the state department to ante up and another 
corner was turned in his twilight months in the white house only 
his commitment to guerrillas trying to overthrow the sandinista 
government in nicaragua remains uncolored by the pragmatic fact 
that the contras are not making much headway 
on arms control after campaigning in 1980 against all major 
accords with the soviet union and putting negotiations on a back 
burner for months reagan gradually adopted a stance that even 
diehard opponents grudgingly acknowledged was far friendlier to 
arms control than they had expected 
they still are worried he may try to unravel the 1972 
antiballistic missile treaty before heading home to california 
but the new 1987 accord to ban intermediaterange nuclear missiles 
is safely on the books 
it stands as the only ussoviet agreement to eliminate an 
entire category of nuclear weapons and it was negotiated on 
reagans watch 
meanwhile four summit meetings with soviet leader mikhail s 
gorbachev have produced a conciliatory stance in the white house 
that is in striking contrast to early reagan rhetorical flourishes 
that included castigating moscow as an evil empire 
until november 1985 he was the first american president since 
herbert hoover not to have met with a soviet leader now he has 
held more oneonone superpower summits than any of them 
ironically reagan has moderated his arms control policy to such 
an extent that michael dukakis who is a liberal democrat 
suggested this week in outlining a nuclear missile strategy agenda 
that his views were not that far from the presidents 
the biggest difference is over reagans strategic defense 
initiative dukakis said he would stop pouring billions and 
billions of dollars into the pursuit of a spacebased defense 
against soviet ballistic missiles but he said he would continue a 
modest research program into possible missile defenses 
the republican candidate vice president george bush who 
projected himself in 1980 as a moderate alternative to reagans 
deep conservatism is working overtime meanwhile to align himself 
with reagans foreign policy initiatives his pitch essentially is 
that he would continue along the same course if he is elected 
having been part of the administration bushs job in lining up 
with reagan policies is hardly as difficult as the task confronting 
dukakis 
but the democratic candidates agenda on weapons moved him 
closer to reagan 
dukakis has voiced concerns about the costs of the b1 bomber 
and the midgetman missile but he endorsed production of the 
trident ii submarinelaunched missile and four other weapons 
more significant perhaps was his vow that well use force 
when its necessary to protect our territory our citizens or our 
vital interests to meet our treaty commitments and to deter or to 
respond to terrorist attacks 
the words were dukakiss but if you close your eyes and let your 
mind drift back to 1980 they might just as well have been ronald 
reagans 
