<TEXT>
the nations heartland is challenging 
swedens generous refugee policy raising fears that latent racism 
may be bubbling to the surface 
its happening in sjobo a small southern farming town where the 
tallest building is three stories high downtown is one street and 
everyone knows just about everybody else 
the 15000 citizens of the town and the surrounding district are 
holding a referendum sunday on whether to accept about 30 refugees 
it is a local issue but the question is drawing national 
attention and is dominating the final weeks of the campaign for the 
parliamentary election on the same day 
government figures say that from 1983 to 1987 62600 people 
sought political asylum in sweden a country of 84 million people 
making it the highest per capita rate in europe 
last year 245 of swedens 284 municipal districts took in 18000 
newcomers as the government tried to spread them outside stockholm 
and other cities where housing is scarce 
when the request came to sjobo the town council balked it 
voted last autumn by 2524 to put the question to a popular vote 
residents say the issue has split families friends and even the 
towns only church distrust and anger stop people from talking 
about it any more and a sullenness has fallen on the town 
a lot of people are very ashamed its terrible said 
madeleine ramel head of the local social welfare board the town 
has changed 
mrs ramel said the fight in sjobo may spread to other 
communities that have been reluctant to take in refugees but that 
have been too afraid of public scorn to refuse 
it is dangerous to ignore signals and what is happening in 
sjobo is one of the signals said mrs ramel 
the immigration department has said sjobo could have a say in 
which immigrants would be sent the decision has been postponed 
until after the referendum 
an influx of immigrants from iran lebanon and south america has 
spawned a rightwing backlash in france denmark and other european 
countries but that has not happened in sweden 
a lot of swedes have a negative attitude toward immigrants it 
