<TEXT>
the tiny island nation of singapore has turned 
into a prime market for american poultry particularly cut up parts 
of chickens an agriculture department trade analyst says 
peter kurz of the departments foreign agricultural service 
until recently the agencys trade officer in singapore said the 
countrys decision to eliminate pig farms is behind the poultry 
boom 
in a drive for a cleaner environment singapore has increased 
the tempo in eliminating all pig farms kurz said since many 
singapore pig farms also have poultry operations the number of 
poultry farms also has declined sharply 
consequently poultry production has dropped causing 
singapores poultry imports to rise to record levels 
kurz who now is serving with the usda agency in washington 
writes about the singapore poultry boom in the october issue of 
foreign agriculture magazine 
imports of chicken parts were up 20 percent with the united 
states accounting for more than half nearly 25000 metric tons 
that was about six times the level of imports from thailand the 
nearest rival 
meanwhile singapores imports of frozen whole chickens dropped 
14 percent last year reflecting a local preference for live 
poultry imported from malaysia kurz said subsidized shipments of 
frozen whole chickens from the european economic community have 
held us competition to a minimum 
however export opportunities for us suppliers may lie in 
the emerging market for breakfast meats particularly turkey roll 
and turkey meat kurz said 
us shipments of chilled and frozen ducks geese turkeys and 
guinea fowl also have increased and occupied a commanding 
position in the singapore market in 1987 he said 
is there a future for american poultry producers in singapore a 
country less than a fourth the size of rhode island and a 
population of 25 million 
everyone involved in this market from breeders to retailers 
believes that singapores poultry consumption especially chicken 
meat will rise although prices appear to be headed upward 
kurz said 
the price hikes and the conversion to a pigfree environment 
do not deter optimistic forecasts as more fastfood outlets and 
the restaurant trade boost the consumption of chicken he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
limited feed supplies could slow chinas 
ambitious drive to boost livestock and poultry production an 
agriculture department report says 
the current fiveyear plan for increasing the output of meat 18 
percent from 193 million metric tons in 1985 to 2275 million 
metric tons by 1990 is meeting with some success the report by the 
departments foreign agricultural service said thursday 
the limiting factor in chinese livestock and poultry 
production gains will be feed supplies the report said in 
turn feed grain imports will be constrained in the next two to 
three years by chinas ability to earn sufficient foreign exchange 
for these purchases 
china is an important but sometimes erratic market for us 
farmers and the livestock sector is watched closely for signs that 
more grain and feed sales may be developing 
one of the problems cited in the report which was included in 
the october issue of foreign agriculture magazine is this years 
rise in world grain prices caused by tighter supplies resulting 
primarily from the us drought 
should world commodity prices remain high the chinese 
government is likely to squeeze exports of corn and soybeans out of 
the domestic market in order to earn badly needed foreign 
exchange the report said 
in 198586 it said china exported more than 6 million tons of 
corn from its northern provinces while importing 400000 tons into 
the south 
as in the past china will continue to export soybeans for 
foreign exchange and barter with japan the ussr and other 
asian countries the report said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department is seeking 
permission from the environmental protection agency to fieldtest a 
genetically engineered bacterium to control a serious disease of 
wheat 
officials said thursday that the test if approved by epa would 
begin next month on a 15acre site at washington state unversitys 
agriculture facility near pullman wash the test would be 
conducted by usda monsanto co and the university 
the test would involve a usdadiscovered strain of a bacterium 
pseudomonas which controls the wheat disease called take all 
the bacterium was genetically altered by monsanto so it can be 
tracked easily in the field 
before the bacterium can be turned into a commercial product 
for use by farmers to control take all we need to know exactly 
what happens when it is released into a field said r james cook 
of the departments agricultural research service 
cook said that among other things scientists need to know 
whether the bacterium spreads into surrounding plants or water or 
if it survives into the following season 
cook and his colleagues at the agencys root disease and 
biological control research laboratory in pullman discovered the 
bacterium strain and conducted seven years of tests to prove its 
ability to control the wheat disease the department said 
 
