<TEXT>
the carefully choreographed steps by the 
government and opposition toward a broadbased national dialogue 
represent the most significant opening in polands political 
impasse since the 1981 martial law crackdown 
but serious obstacles remain before any ompromise can be reached 
that would bridge the chasm dividing polish authorities from the 
east blocs largest and bestorganized opposition movement 
after their second working meeting in 16 days thursday 
solidarity leader lech walesa and interior minister gen czeslaw 
kiszczak indicated that efforts toward roundtable talks 
broadbased discussions on polands future were on track 
another meeting today involves for the first time other 
solidarity representatives and members of the official trade union 
alliance opzz 
opposition activists appeared satisfied that authorities are 
willing in principle to relegalize solidarity in a form yet to be 
negotiated 
i would say that both sides are not terribly far apart as far 
as basic things are concerned said prosolidarity journalist 
krzysztof sliwinski 
what remains to be seen he said is how different the new 
solidarity would be from the mass social movement of 198081 
ludwig krasucki an editor of the communist party monthly nowe 
drogi said in an interview there was a better than 50 percent 
chance that union pluralism would be allowed 
it cannot be easy he said it needs some time and then i 
think we will open a process of negotiation 
the government overtures after seven years of deadlock comes 
amid signs that communist authorities are psychologically prepared 
to accept the permanent existence of an organized political 
opposition 
some officially published commentaries have even gone so far as 
to praise the effects of an active opposition movement 
states having a strong political opposition keep developing 
while the socialist states are sinking in crisis said one 
particularly startling commentary in the officially published 
weekly odrozenie 
after struggling without marked success to govern alone the 
ruling polish united workers communist party led by gen wojciech 
jaruzelski is hoping through roundtable talks with walesa to tap 
the energy of the opposition that it crushed in 1981 
but there is a catch whatever formula is devised it must 
somehow guarantee that the communist party keeps the dominant role 
proposals have been floated in the press such as reserving a 
significant minority of parliament seats for the opposition or 
creating a new upper chamber of parliament with limited powers 
which would not have a guaranteed majority of communist deputies 
but it is highly uncertain whether polands skeptical and 
pragmatic opposition would ever accept anything that smacked of 
tokenism or being coopted by the system 
krasucki said the majority of party membership is ready for a 
big compromise in political reform and that he thought 
jaruzelski would bring about the changes 
but a grand old man of the polish opposition movement socialist 
jan jozef lipski said he was skeptical of any speedy promises of 
reform 
the direction of changes will get deeper thats for sure 
he said but it will take much more time 
the governments decision to enter into talks taken in the 
midst of last months strikes and signs that polands downward 
economic spiral is worsening gives the appearance of a country 
coming full circle 
poland was also in dire economic straits in 1980 when strikes 
lifted the then unknown walesa into the role of spokesman for an 
entire societys grievances 
a tide of social unrest forced authorities then to deal with 
walesa but over the next 15 months it was confrontation not 
acceptance that characterized government actions toward the union 
the december 1981 martial law crackdown was merely the final blow 
outlawing solidarity and detaining thousands of its supporters 
only exacerbated the governments problems the economy continued 
to falter and the government had little domestic support to draw 
upon when mounting foreign debt forced it into unpopular austerity 
measures 
solidarity in turn has been frustrated by its outlaw status 
which has hampered its effectiveness as a trade union by subjecting 
members to legal reprisals and preventing them from working openly 
to organize factories 
both sides tired and fed up with the status quo would like to 
see a change 
possible outlines of a compromise emerged in the first interview 
with walesa published in the official polish press since the 
martial law crackdown 
since authorities will not totally abandon the official trade 
unions set up after solidarity a major question is how both 
solidarity and those unions can exist in the same workplaces 
speaking to the monthly konfrontacje walesa cited the example 
of west germany where multiple unions coexist in a single factory 
and negotiate jointly with management through elected workers 
councils 
