designed to protect american industry from foreign competition 
the bill won approval last week only to remain bottled up in the 
senate when opponents seized on a technicality to delay it 
thursdays vote freed the bill from that snarl and sent it to 
the house 
the bill would freeze textile and apparel imports at 1987 levels 
and limit growth to 1 percent annually starting next year it would 
hold nonrubber footwear imports to 1987 levels and ban further 
increases in foreign producers share of the us market 
congress has been fighting over new import curbs for three 
years with sponsors saying they are needed to save both american 
jobs and an industry that is vital to the nations defense critics 
concede apparel companies have problems but say the textile 
industry is flourishing 
indeed opponents credit stepped up competition from overseas 
with prodding the textile industry to modernize they attribute a 
wave of layoffs since the early 1980s to increased automation 
president reagan vetoed an earlier version of the bill in 1985 
saying it would narrow consumer choices and cost more jobs than it 
would save 
the current version is moving slowly forward amid threats of 
another presidential veto 
the presidents going to veto it fortunately and i hope that 
we have the votes to sustain the veto sen bob packwood rore 
told the senate america cannot turn its back on the world its 
going to be part of it and frankly id rather participate in 
it 
textile forces had hoped that the house would give swift 
approval to the four changes that the senate made since the house 
passed the bill a year ago 
but the house ways and means committee voted wednesday to 
negotiate the differences in a housesenate conference committee 
a conference just delays the time hollings complained to 
