<TEXT>
they were told to bring their own 
food drinks and blankets but warned to leave their pets booze 
and guns at home and they did 
as hurricane gilbert perhaps the mostfeared storm of its kind 
approached the texas coast residents fled their homes taking 
bedrolls and food supplies to red cross shelters on higher ground 
in this southernmost texas city where the eye of gilbert was 
predicted to pass sometime this evening 750 people filled the 
civic auditorium to its capacity within four hours while hundreds 
of others crowded into schools 
for some their flight to the shelters was reminiscent of 
hurricane beulah which struck brownsville in 1980 and hurricane 
allen which landed north of brownsville the same year 
we brought food water some milk but my husband forgot the 
stereo and all our medicine but i think we will be all right 
said 77yearold maria cardenas a diabetic in a wheelchair 
families staked out perimeters on the floor of the civic center 
placing blankets sheets and pillows on the floor next to bags of 
food and ice chests filled with meats and soft drinks 
some children brought their plastic toys and some brought their 
teddy bears while others turned on their small radios and tuned in 
to news of the storm 
most of the people who come here or to other shelters in the 
rio grande valley are those who dont have transportation to go 
