<TEXT>
only one opposition candidate was elected 
earlier this month but two of the losers will be appointed to join 
him in parliament under a controversial measure designed to ensure 
opposing voices are heard 
the measure whereby the two members will get 
nonconstituency seats was introduced before the last polls in 
1984 by amending the constitution to create limited opposition 
after the peoples action party won every seat in the four previous 
general elections 
the pap has been in power since 1959 under prime minister lee 
kuan yew 
lee said that in two years of cabinet discussion such 
alternatives as proportional representation and a second chamber in 
parliament were considered and rejected as unsuitable for this 
island republic of 26 million people 
opposition politicians condemned the new measure as a means of 
perpetuating pap rule 
chaim see tong of the singapore democratic party was the only 
opposition candidate to win at the polls on sept 3 the pap took 
80 of 81 seats 11 of them unopposed and 646 percent of the 
valid votes cast 
chaim who was first elected in 1984 repeated his rejection of 
nonconstituency seats sunday 
according to the measure the seats are offered to the three 
best performers among the opposition losers if one or two 
opposition candidates manage to win at the polls as chaim did 
extra seats are added up to a total of three 
those appointed must have polled at least 15 percent of the vote 
in their constituencies and must belong to a political party 
they enjoy most of the rights and privileges of the other 81 
parliament members and can speak on any issue but they cannot vote 
on noconfidence motions proposals to amend the constitution or 
bills to supply funds to the government or tax money from the 
people they represent no constituency 
opposition parties rejected the one appointment offered after 
the 1984 election when chaim and workers party leader jb 
jeyaretnam were voted into parliament 
jeyaretnam denounced the measure then as a ruse to try to keep 
the electorate thinking of the pap as the only government 
providing for everything including opposition mps 
jeyaretnam still heads the workers party but was ousted from 
parliament and disqualified for five years from 1986 for allegedly 
falsifying party records 
after a week of heated intraparty debate jeyaretnam announced 
saturday that two of its losers would accept the offer to enter 
parliament if he had said no seats would have been offered to the 
next two highestpolling losers 
jeyaretnam said his party remained opposed to the concept of 
nonconstituency seats and its acceptance of them should not be 
regarded as a precedent for the partys decision in future cases 
the workers party will be represented by lawyer francis seow 
and a physician lee siew choh 
seow 59 a former solicitor general and president of the law 
society is a newcomer to party politics and was widely expected to 
run as an independent 
he was released on july 16 after 72 days in jail under the 
countrys internal security act which permits detention without 
trial the government alleged that seow conspired with us 
diplomats to increase the parliamentary opposition to the 
government 
however he has since been accused of income tax evasion and 
faces trial in december if convicted seow would lose his 
parliament seat 
