<TEXT>
doctors often incorrectly instruct patients on 
using nicotine gum or fail to prescribe it at all even though it 
can help heavy smokers quit according to studies published today 
most internists prescribe nicotine gum to fewer than 25 
percent of patients who try to quit smoking said one of five 
smokingrelated studies in todays journal of the american medical 
association there is a widespread need for physician education 
about how to use nicotine gum more effectively 
for instance nearly 40 percent of 208 internists surveyed in 
the study said they would prescribe nicotine gum to help patients 
cut down on smoking violating a key guideline for using it the 
manufacturers guidelines call for patients to stop smoking 
completely before using it 
and onefourth of the internists surveyed said they had recently 
prescribed sedatives to help patients stop smoking although 
there is no evidence that sedatives are useful for that 
purpose said the study by dr steven r cummings and colleagues at 
the university of california medical school in san francisco 
i would guess that the confusion and difficulties with using 
the gum are very widespread cummings said 
nicotine gum a prescription drug marketed under the trade name 
nicorette by lakeside pharmaceuticals of cincinnati can be an 
effective tool to help some people quit smoking particularly heavy 
smokers concluded three other studies in the journal 
but one study found that 34 of 538 patients or 68 percent who 
were given nicotine gum to help them quit smoking were still 
chewing it after a year 
those longterm gum chewers also represented 25 percent of the 
patients who succeeded in staying off cigarettes for a year said 
the report by researchers at the university of london 
i dont think physicians ought to supply it just 
willynilly said dr stephen p fortmann an assistant professor 
at the stanford university school of medicine most people whove 
quit smoking did it before the gum was available so were by 
no means advocating it 
the gum shouldnt be seen as either a miracle or as a 
necessity but as a useful adjunct 
another study in the journal found that heavy smokers those 
who consume more than 25 cigarettes daily are more physically 
addicted to nicotine and have a harder time quitting than people 
who smoke no more than 15 cigarettes a day 
that study suggested nicotine gum might better help heavy 
smokers overcome withdrawal symptoms caused by their physical 
addiction when they stop 
lakeside spokesman bill donaldson said the manufacturer 
estimates 2 million people have quit smoking by using nicotine gum 
as part of a stopsmoking program since nicorette was introduced in 
1985 
he said the company had no reports of patients becoming addicted 
to nicotine from the gum itself any dependence on the gum is a 
transference of the patients nicotine addiction from smoking and 
is part of the weaning process donaldson said 
