<TEXT>
a federal appeals court today struck down two 
previous orders that had directed the environmental protection 
agency to recalculate automobile fuel economy ratings 
the order by the full us circuit court of appeals here 
relieves the epa of any obligation to comply with the courts 
previous orders to recalculate the fuel economy ratings according 
to a method that could cost ford motor co and general motors corp 
millions of dollars in fines 
the decision today made in a brief order by the courts 11 
members reversed a 55 vote taken may 17 that had upheld a 1986 
ruling by a threejudge panel that the fuel standards be 
recalculated 
in the previous vote the court divided along bitter ideological 
lines over whether the center for auto safety and other petitioners 
had standing to challenge the epas 1985 decision to relax the 
fueleconomy standards 
the epa action had lowered penalties that ford and gm would be 
assessed for failing to meet fleetwide fuel economy standards set 
under the environmental policy and conservation act of 1975 
the law requires manufacturers to be fined 5 for each tenth of 
a mile a car model falls short of the milespergallon standard set 
by the epa regulations manufacturers are given credits for models 
that surpass the standards that can be carried over to subsequent 
model years 
the court said today that after considering the epas motion to 
reconsider that decision we have decided that our original 
disposition was not an appropriate one 
we now hold that as a majority of the court was unable to 
satisfy itself that the court had jurisdiction the court should 
not have taken any affirmative action on the merits including 
reinstatement of the panel opinion the court said in an unsigned 
order 
in may the court had said that it would uphold the 1986 ruling 
but that that holding would not become a legal precedent because 
the circuit judges could not agree on the issue of legal standing 
</TEXT>
