<TEXT>
federal officials are proposing new rules 
aimed at preventing disasters like last years collapse of an 
apartment building that killed 28 construction workers 
the us occupational safety and health administrations 
proposed rules may not be implemented until next summer after the 
administration evaluates comment on the plan 
the proposal applies only to liftslab techniques which were 
being used when the partially completed lambiance plaza collapsed 
the technique is a seldomused method in which concrete floor 
slabs are poured on the ground one on top of the other after the 
slabs are cured they are jacked upwards along vertical steel 
columns then fastened at their proper levels 
an osha official roy gurnham said the rules clarify the 
requirement that all nonessential workers be cleared from a 
liftslab building while the floors are being lifted 
the rule always has been in effect but was interpreted by 
workers and managers to mean that construction crews could work 
below a floor that was fastened 
osha officials previously assumed that a permanent floor above 
the workers would break the fall of a higher concrete floor that 
slipped and fell 
other portions of the new rules would require that a qualified 
designer design liftslab projects 
also the rules say that all jacks lifting the floors should be 
able to lift 25 times the weight expected to be applied and all 
slabs should be lifted in a level position 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

