<TEXT>
former navy secretary john lehman said friday 
the navy should use fewer consultants but he strongly defended his 
tenure against criticism arising from the current pentagon bribery 
investigation 
the changes that we made in the navy procurement system were 
deep and fundamental lehman told the house armed services 
committee i do not believe that any of the changes that we made 
could by their nature increase the incidence of improper behavior 
lehman resigned last year after leading the naval buildup that 
was a key part of president reagans defense program 
but the navy is now the center of a bribery investigation by 
federal prosecutors who are looking at allegations of payoffs and 
bribes from consultants many of whom were former pentagon 
employees 
the consultants were seeking information from pentagon officials 
about details of contracts information that could make the 
difference in winning multimillion dollar contracts no charges 
have yet been filed 
a key figure of the investigation is melvyn paisley the former 
assistant navy secretary for research and engineering and a close 
associate of lehman during their navy tenure paisley resigned and 
became a highpriced consultant shortly after lehman quit to take a 
wall street job in april 1987 
lehmans testimony to the committee was his first major public 
comment since the investigation became public three months ago 
lehman declined to talk about details of the investigation and 
committee members did not ask him for specifics because they did 
not want to affect the probe 
lehman noted the navy has more consultants than the other 
services chiefly because the navy has fewer officers consultants 
do work for the navy performed by officers in the air force and 
army he said 
but i was never comfortable with the dependence on 
consultants lehman said detailing what he said were generally 
unsuccessful efforts to reduce the number of consultants 
consultants are essential but we do have too many he said 
the navy could substantially reduce its reliance on consultants 
two reforms suggested in the wake of the investigation are 
requiring consultants to register and requiring them to disclose 
all their contracts to prevent conflicts of interest lehman 
endorsed those changes 
the combative former official also strongly defended changes he 
made during his tenure some critics have suggested the changes 
such as more centralized management and elimination of some layers 
of bureaucracy caused the climate which led to the investigation 
with regard to strong centralized policymaking and 
decentralized execution i see no way that either principle 
increases the opportunity for waste fraud and abuse he said 
i am very proud of the achievements made in rebuilding the 
navy during my tenure he said i do believe the changes that 
led to that success made the system by its nature more susceptible 
to waste fraud and abuse 
overall said lehman the pentagon should be reorganized to give 
much more authority for daily decisions to lowerlevel personnel 
rather than top officials he opposed the creation of a single 
purchasing czar a change proposed by some legislators 
in rough book value the department of defense equals the top 
30 companies on the fortune 500 list combined he said and yet 
the pentagon is organized in theory like a small business with all 
operational authority and decisionmaking drawn up in one 
centralized office 
he proposed that the secretary of defense simply make policy 
and turn all other major decisions over to the three services 
the staff should also be reduced by half he said and that goal 
could be easily achieved 
normal attrition in the military and civil service is about 8 
percent per year so careful use of hiring freezes brings a rapid 
natural shrinkage he said increased opportunity for voluntary 
early retirement with pensions or large severance payments would 
enable a new administration to cut the pentagon bureaucracy by 30 
