<TEXT>
george bushs assault on michael dukakis fiscal 
record renews a debate over statistics that are generally favorable 
to dukakis but show some holes in massachusetts economic rebound 
bush struck at the heart of dukakis candidacy his stewardship 
of massachusetts during its economic boom with a speech thursday 
that selectively used statistics to point out chinks in the state 
financial record but that also gave a misleading characterization 
of the states tax picture 
you can pretty much do what you want with selected 
statistics said betsy hodeling spokeswoman for dukakis 
department of revenue if you wanted to call day night you could 
probably find a statistic to support that 
an obvious example is jobs bush cited the states loss of 
26000 manufacturing jobs since 1983 state officials have put the 
number closer to 100000 but they also cite a net gain of more than 
400000 jobs since 1983 
bush said massachusetts spending increased between 1983 and 1987 
at a rate faster than any other state and that tax increases in 
that period were second only to connecticut 
dukakis administration officials did not dispute bushs 
assertion on spending state budgets have grown by nearly 1 
billion a year since 1983 fueled by soaring state revenues much 
of the increased spending has been in the form of aid to cities and 
towns hurt by a voterapproved property tax cap and the reagan 
administrations decision to halt revenue sharing with 
municipalities 
on the tax side however administration officials denounced 
bushs figures which do not take into account the record increase 
in percapita income in massachusetts over the fouryear period the 
vice president cited 
during that period state taxes have been cut several times 
including the repeal of a surtax dukakis authored in 1975 his 
first year as governor dukakis initially opposed most of the tax 
cuts 
bush chose the per capita figures because they appear to 
show that taxes went up said hodeling what they fail to show 
is that people here are making a lot more money so of course they 
are paying more taxes percentagewise taxes have been cut 
bush cited the surtax to support his position that dukakis was 
the biggest tax raiser in massachusetts history dukakis sought the 
increase to erase a 600 million deficit inherited from his 
republican predecessor 
there are probably a zillion ways to measure taxes said 
house republican leader steven pierce who met with bush in july to 
discuss state finances in any political campaign you have 
charges and countercharges and statistics can be used to support a 
variety of things 
the vice president chided dukakis for approving 74 billion in 
longterm borrowing for capital projects during his tenure and for 
not fully funding the states pension system 
however wall streets two major bond rating agencies recently 
termed massachusetts longterm debt moderate compared to many 
states and said its economy appeared strong enough to support the 
debt and it was dukakis who last year convinced the legislature to 
pass a plan to fund the pension system an effort which he had made 
a priority in his second and third terms dukakis did tap into 
surplus pension funds this year to help offset a 450 million 
revenue shortfall 
bush also asserted that dukakis has turned a state surplus into 
a deficit that could grow to 700 million by the end of the current 
fiscal year 
dukakis last year won passage of about 180 million in new taxes 
and cut state spending by more than 200 million to end fiscal 1988 
with a 67 million surplus and to support revenue projections in 
the current budget 
many legislators most of them republicans have predicted the 
state will fall short of money again this year but even dukakis 
harshest critics say it is too early to make a credible assessment 
i personally think 700 million is a reasonable estimate but 
you cant prove it said barbara anderson executive director of 
citizens for limited taxation and a dukakis enemy nobody can 
prove it but candidates snipe at each other 
dukakis has stood behind his revenue projections but has 
promised to cut spending if necessary 
he was forced into that position last year and the state has had 
to borrow on a shortterm basis for the first time since 1980 
issuing more than 1 billion in notes in the past eight months to 
pay its bills that will cost taxpayers about 20 million in 
interest payments 
