<TEXT>
a federal appeals court reversed two previous 
court decisions and let stand friday changes the government imposed 
three years ago in the way automobile fuel economy is tested 
critics of the 1985 changes by the environmental protection 
agency had charged that the changes had allowed automakers to save 
millions of dollars in penalties for failing to meet fuel economy 
standards 
a threejudge panel and later the us circuit court of appeals 
had ruled in favor of a suit filed by the center for auto safety 
challenging the epas 1985 decision which eased methods used by 
automakers to determine gas mileage for each of their car models 
those tests are used to determine fleetwide fuel economy 
figures that each automaker must meet under separate regulations 
the national highway traffic safety administration establishes the 
fleet average and if an automaker does not meet the average and 
does not have credits from past years it must pay a civil penalty 
the full appeals court said friday that the two previous 
rulings in 1986 and last may were in error as a result the epa 
testing procedures imposed in 1985 will stand 
the full 11member appeals court said that it had not been 
determined that the center for auto safety had standing to 
challenge the regulatory change by the epa noting that the court 
that issued the earlier decision had been sharply divided on that 
issue 
the ruling last may in favor of the center for auto safety suit 
came in a 55 vote 
we now hold that as a majority of the court was unable to 
satisfy itself that the court had jurisdiction the court should 
not have taken any affirmative action on the merits of the 
case the court said friday 
the issue involves testing methods used by the automakers for 
determining the fuel economy of each car model the epa in 1985 
agreed to allow a series of technical changes in those methods 
which critics said made it easier for the manufacturers to attain 
higher mileage figures and in turn made it easier to meet 
fleetwide fuel economy requirements 
as a result the suit argued manufacturers such as ford motor 
co and general motors corp which were having difficulty meeting 
the fuel economy requirements anyway saved millions of dollars in 
penalties 
the effect of todays decision is to let gm and ford off the 
hook from having to pay any penalties for failing to comply with 
fuel economy standards in previous model years said cornish 
hitchcock an attorney for the center for auto safety 
the automakers welcomed the appeals court decision 
it reinstates epas original rulemaking which ford believes 
did account for the effects of changing test procedures on our 
corporate average fuel economy said donald buist director of 
fords automotive emissions and fuel economy office in dearborn 
mich 
william h noack a washingtonbased spokesman for general 
motors said the company welcomed the decision but said it 
would have no effect on gms fleetwide fuel efficiency performance 
for 1988 through 1990 models 
federal law requires a 275 miles per gallon fleetwide fuel 
economy standards for 198990 model cars but nhtsa has proposed 
lowering that to 265 mpg it has lowered it to 26 mpg in each of 
the past three model years arguing that consumer demand for large 
less fuel efficient cars make the 275 standard difficult for 
automakers to reach 
</TEXT>
