<TEXT>
fires in yellowstone 
national park picked up again friday but fire officials were 
confident moisture from storms last weekend and work since then 
would prevent the fires from growing 
this week i think theyre fairly confident with the measures 
theyve taken during the early part of this week that theyll be 
able to hold the fires said fire information officer linda 
miller i think theyre fairly confident that they wont have any 
major problems 
the fires which now form one huge blaze have affected 11 
million acres of the 22 millionacre park but according to new 
infrared scans they have burned only about 50 percent to 60 
percent of the land within fire perimeters 
park officials said the fires remained inside fire perimeters 
friday 
i dont think anything slopped over any lines said park 
spokeswoman sonya capek 
temperatures in the park only reached the mid60s and steady 
winds approached 35 mph the weather forecast offered some good 
news for saturday with a chance of light snowshowers in the 
afternoon and temperatures in the 50s the storm also could bring 
some heavy winds but capek said the high humidity and cold 
temperatures will keep the fires down 
firefighters had taken advantage of the wet cold weather 
earlier in the week to strengthen existing lines around fires and 
extend lines and by friday had contained 50 percent of the 
335500acre north fork fire the most troublesome of the blazes in 
the park 
blazes also burned friday in montana idaho oregon and 
washington state as the worst fire season in 30 years continued 
more than 4 million acres including 21 million acres in alaska 
have gone up in smoke 
denny bungarz north fork fire incident commander said 
officials believe it would take seven days of continued dry weather 
before yellowstone would return to the tinderdry conditions that 
allowed fires to grow by thousands of acres daily 
and 700 marines from camp pendleton in california reached the 
park friday to help with firefighting efforts bringing the 
military force in the countrys first national park to 4100 
thirty canadian firefighters arrived friday the first canadian 
crew to arrive since the us forest service accepted that 
countrys offer to help 
