<TEXT>
ashland oil inc officials have reacted 
bitterly to criminal charges lodged against the company for a 
massive oil spill saying the charges will impair efforts to comply 
with environmental laws 
the company is disappointed that criminal actions will be 
pursued in light of ashlands efforts to mitigate the spills 
impact and the fact that the company quickly accepted 
responsibility for the incident ashland spokesman roger schrum 
said thursday 
on thursday a federal grand jury indicted ashland for 
violations of the federal clean water and the refuse acts the 
first criminal charges arising from the jan 2 spill that 
contaminated drinking water in three states 
us attorney j alan johnson said the two misdemeanor counts 
were the most stringent that could be brought because federal 
environmental laws do not contain felony provisions for 
corporations for such offenses 
were doing the best we can he said were following the 
evidence based on the law that exists here 
conviction carries a maximum penalty of a 200000 fine on each 
count or double the monetary loss suffered as a result of the 
criminal conduct so far the losses amount to more than 10 
million johnson said 
schrum said ashland voluntarily has paid more than 114 million 
for cleanup costs and to reimburse claims from individuals 
businesses and government agencies 
the decision to prosecute ashland goes against past practices by 
the justice department to pursue criminal violations only in 
instances of deliberate acts he said 
we think such actions impair rather than promote environmental 
compliance schrum said 
the spill occurred when an ashland oil riverside storage tank at 
the companys floreffe terminal in jefferson near pittsburgh 
collapsed while being filled with 38 million gallons of fuel oil 
about 1 million gallons escaped the containment dikes at the 
facility and more than 700000 gallons spilled into the 
monongahela river and traveled downstream well beyond the rivers 
confluence with the ohio river 
the government said the accident represented one of the largest 
inland oil spills in the nations history affecting drinking water 
supplies and plant and animal life in pennsylvania ohio and west 
virginia about 23000 suburban pittsburgh residents went without 
tap water for almost a week 
the indictment said ashland had disassembled a 48yearold oil 
storage tank near cleveland in 1986 and then reassembled it at the 
floreffe terminal it was placed in service in august 1987 
in may investigators for an independent research institute that 
studied the accident said a dimesize flaw in the tanks brittle 
steel walls caused the collapse aggravating the condition were the 
relative weakness of the world war iiera steel pressure from the 
diesel fuel and cold weather according to the battelle memorial 
institute 
besides failing to obtain all necessary local permits for 
erecting the tank ashland said it failed to fill the tank with 
water before use a test recommended by the american petroleum 
institute an industry group 
johnson said the indictment does not end the federal 
governments investigation of the oil spill he said the government 
still must determine if any ashland employees or officials violated 
the law 
the state attorney generals office also is conducting a 
criminal investigation but has brought no charges 
in a separate civil action in july the justice department filed 
a proposed consent decree requiring ashland based in ashland ky 
to complete the cleanup of the spill and to reimburse the 
government 680000 for emergency response work by federal agencies 
ashland has agreed to the decrees terms 
