<TEXT>
the nuclear regulatory commission has set the 
stage for two key votes that could remove the final regulatory 
obstacles in the seabrook nh plants long road toward a 
lowpower operating license 
if the commission acts today in favor of the plant seabrook 
could be eligible for the license within 30 days but massachusetts 
officials have vowed to fight the license in federal court 
the lowpower license has been a key pressure point in the 
struggle between seabrook owners the nuclear industry and new 
hampshire state officials on one side and massachusetts gov 
michael s dukakis local officials and antinuclear activists on 
the other 
seabrook must obtain the license which would allow it to test 
the reactor at 5 percent of capacity before securing a fullpower 
commercial operating license 
the nrc is to decide two issues the first is whether to allow a 
reactor to operate at low power without having an emergency system 
in place to alert neighbors in case of a plant accident 
massachusetts municipalities in the 10mile zone forced seabrook 
officials to remove the sirens 
under the new rule the siren system would have to be in place 
only for fullpower license consideration seabrook officials are 
working on plans to mount sirens on trucks and helicopters 
the second issue which was tentatively scheduled for an nrc 
vote was a petition by opponents urging the commission to break 
from its regulations and consider the financial condition of the 
plants owners 
the lead owner public service company of new hampshire filed 
for bankruptcy protection in january public service owns 36 
percent of the plant 
in june massachusetts municipal wholesale electric co which 
is the fourth largest seabrook shareholder at 12 percent announced 
it was withdrawing from the project and would stop making its 2 
millionamonth payments 
for opponents blocking the lowpower license is critical 
because they say 5 percent power tests would contaminate the 
facility with radioactive fuel ruling out a future conversion to a 
gasfired plant or other facility advocated by nuclear critics 
plant officials say the tests would not rule out a conversion 
seabrook opponents believe plant owners and the commission are 
trying to win lowpower license approval before the possibility of 
encountering a dukakis presidency that could further hinder the 
licensing process 
dukakis the democratic presidential nominee says it would be 
impossible to quickly evacuate residents from the massachusetts 
seacoast towns that lie within the plants 10mile emergency 
evacuation zone an area that swells with summer tourists and has 
congested roads on normal days 
the idle 56 billion reactor is losing 50 million each month 
in maintenance and finance costs 
