<TEXT>
business inventories rose only a modest 03 
percent in july even though sales were down by 02 percent the 
government said today 
the commerce department said inventories held on shelves and 
backlots rose 22 billion to a seasonally adjusted 7337 billion 
while sales edged down by 12 billion 
the july gain in inventories followed a 08 percent rise in june 
and was the 19th consecutive month without a decline however the 
july increase was the smallest since a 02 percent rise in august 
1987 
economists sometimes take rising inventories as a sign of 
economic weakness too many goods in reserve could lead to 
production cuts and layoffs at manufacturing plants however 
analysts have not been worried over the past year because the 
inventory gain has simply been keeping up with strong sales 
the july drop in sales was the first since november and followed 
a strong jump of 14 percent in june 
the june inventory accumulation was led by 05 percent increases 
at both the manufacturing and wholesale levels inventories shrank 
by 01 percent at the retail level where sales have been weakest 
in recent months 
in sales a 09 percent decline at factories more than offset a 
06 percent rise at the wholesale level and a slight 01 percent 
increase at retail stores 
an advance estimate of retail sales for august released 
thursday showed a 02 percent decrease 
the combination of weak sales and slowly rising inventories left 
the inventorytosales ratio unchanged at 15 in july that means 
it would take 15 months to exhaust inventories at the july sales 
pace a ratio not considered abnormally high 
</TEXT>
