<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has ordered the 
detroit news and detroit free press to delay their partial merger 
which could have begun as early as this weekend as the judges 
consider whether the deal should be scrapped altogether 
the us court of appeals for the district of columbia circuit 
late thursday ordered a stay in an order by attorney general edwin 
meese iii allowing the newspapers to merge their business 
production and circulation departments under an exception to 
federal antitrust laws 
michigan citizens for an independent press an organization of 
advertisers and readers opposed to the newspapers joint operating 
agreement had asked for the extension in a motion filed earlier in 
the day 
the court ordered the delay to gain time to study the complex 
case the court clerks office said 
the group last month successfully blocked the immediate merger 
of the newspapers business and production departments in a 
challenge to a decision by thenattorney general edwin meese iii 
allowing the joint operating agreement under the newspaper 
preservation act 
the temporary stay granted by the us district court in 
washington forced the newspapers to recall laidoff employees and 
quickly alter printing plans 
us district judge george revercomb on wednesday rejected the 
challenge and said he would allow the order staying the partial 
merger to expire at 715 pm on saturday 
the appeals courts order thursday means the combination will 
not proceed on that schedule 
the newspapers had not said how quickly then could have begun 
joint production under the agreement after expiration of the 
earlier stay 
free press publisher david lawrence this week said the 
newspapers would begin the operation as soon as they were legally 
cleared to do so 
the court issued its own order staying meeses decision rather 
than granting the opponents request for a stay thereby gaining 
time to study the case without seeming to accept the contentions of 
either side 
after the michigan citizens group made its request assistant 
attorney general john bolton filed an eightpage brief with the 
appeals court opposing any stay of the agreement 
the opponents of the merger have fallen far short of their 
burden of showing that the attorney general acted so mistakenly 
that his decision can be labeled irrational said boltons brief 
bill schultz an attorney for michigan citizens said after the 
appeal was filed that his clients could show a stay was appropriate 
because a lower court judge in granting the earlier stay had 
agreed that allowing the merger to proceed prior to a court ruling 
would produce irreparable injury and be contrary to the public 
interest 
opponents of the agreement argued that meese had ignored 
findings that the free press was not a failing newspaper and that 
financial losses by it and the news were caused by management 
decisions rather than being inherent to the marketplace 
revercomb rejected that contention saying that meese had 
reasonably found that the free press would have already failed were 
it not owned by a large corporate parent knightridder inc 
knightridder had no comment on the appeal said lee ann 
schlatter manager of corporate communications 
gannett also declined comment were simply waiting to see 
what the appeals court does said sheila gibbons public affairs 
manager the news referred inquires to gannett 
the general manager of the free press bob hall said today 
the stay that was issued is really an administrative stay and 
its only issued for the convenience of the court to take some time 
to look at the request for the stay 
the delay just gives the judges a couple of days to look at 
the filings and has no bearing on the merits of the case 
the merger of the newspapers business advertising circulation 
and production departments would result in layoffs of 600 to 800 
employees 
