the farm credit bank of omaha neb will get 
up to 110 million in federal aid the farm credit system 
assistance board announced friday 
eric p thor the boards chief executive officer said the 
assistance was approved after an extensive review of the banks 
current and projected financial situation and proposed credit 
managment plan 
the aid will help the bank regain financial viability and 
save between 150 million and 250 million over the next several 
years he said 
without assistance the bank may not be in a strong enough 
financial position to successfully carry out its plan for the 
future thor said the support provided under the law should 
make the difference 
as authorized by the board the omaha bank will receive the 
assistance by selling up to 110 million in preferred stock to the 
farm credit system financial assistance corp 
the agricultural credit act of 1987 provides that the 
corporation will fund that assistance through the sale of 15year 
bonds and the us treasury will pay interest on those bonds for 
the first five years 
thor said the law also requires the treasury and the farm credit 
system or fcs to each pay half of the interest on the bonds in 
the second five years the fcs will assume full responsibility in 
the final five years and the omaha bank must repay the assistance 
at the end of the 15year period 
the omaha federal land bank and the federal intermediate credit 
bank merged on july 6 forming the farm credit bank of omaha which 
provides comprehensive banking services to farmers and ranchers in 
iowa nebraska south dakota and wyoming 
the 1987 law created the board to work with troubled fcs 
institutions it was chartered on jan 21 1988 and comprises 
three members agriculture secretary richard e lyng acting 
treasury secretary peter mcpherson and indiana farmer william w 
erwin 
